# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: term-rewriting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In mathematical logic and theoretical computer science, an **abstract rewriting system** (also (**abstract**) **reduction system** or **abstract rewrite system**; abbreviated **ARS**) is a formalism that captures the quintessential notion and properties of rewriting systems.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In its simplest form, an ARS is simply a set (of "objects") together with a binary relation, traditionally denoted with $\rightarrow$ ; this definition can be further refined if we index (label) subsets of the binary relation.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Despite its simplicity, an ARS is sufficient to describe important properties of rewriting systems like normal forms, termination, and various notions of confluence.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Historically, there have been several formalizations of rewriting in an abstract setting, each with its idiosyncrasies.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] This is due in part to the fact that some notions are equivalent, see below in this article.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] The formalization that is most commonly encountered in monographs and textbooks, and which is generally followed here, is due to Gérard Huet (1980).
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] An *abstract reduction system* (*ARS*) is the most general (unidimensional) notion about specifying a set of objects and rules that can be applied to transform them.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] More recently, authors use the term *abstract rewriting system* as well.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] (The preference for the word "reduction" here instead of "rewriting" constitutes a departure from the uniform use of "rewriting" in the names of systems that are particularizations of ARS.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] An ARS is a set *A*, whose elements are usually called objects, together with a binary relation on *A*, traditionally denoted by →, and called the **reduction relation**, *rewrite relation* or just **reduction**.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] This (entrenched) terminology using "reduction" is a little misleading, because the relation is not necessarily reducing some measure of the objects.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In some contexts it may be beneficial to distinguish between some subsets of the rules, i.e. some subsets of the reduction relation →, e.g. the entire reduction relation may consist of associativity and commutativity rules.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Consequently, some authors define the reduction relation → as the indexed union of some relations; for instance if ${\rightarrow _{1}\cup \rightarrow _{2}}={\rightarrow }$ , the notation used is (A, →1, →2).
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] As a mathematical object, an ARS is exactly the same as an unlabeled state transition system, and if the relation is considered as an indexed union, then an ARS is the same as a labeled state transition system with the indices being the labels.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] The focus of the study, and the terminology are different however.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In a state transition system one is interested in interpreting the labels as actions, whereas in an ARS the focus is on how objects may be transformed (rewritten) into others.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Suppose the set of objects is *T* = {*a*, *b*, *c*} and the binary relation is given by the rules *a* → *b*, *b* → *a*, *a* → *c*, and *b* → *c*.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Observe that these rules can be applied to both *a* and *b* to get *c*.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Furthermore, nothing can be applied to *c* to transform it any further.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Such a property is clearly an important one.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] First define some basic notions and notations.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] An object *x* in *A* is called *reducible* if there exist some other *y* in *A* and $x\rightarrow y$ ; otherwise it is called *irreducible* or a *normal form*.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] An object *y* is called a normal form of *x* if $x{\stackrel {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ and *y* is irreducible.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] If *x* has a *unique* normal form, then this is usually denoted with $x\downarrow$ .
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In example 1 above, *c* is a normal form, and $c=a\downarrow =b\downarrow$ .
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] If every object has at least one normal form, the ARS is called *normalizing*.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] A related, but weaker notion than the existence of normal forms is that of two objects being *joinable*: *x* and *y* are said to be joinable if there exists some *z* with the property that $x{\stackrel {*}{\rightarrow }}z{\stackrel {*}{\leftarrow }}y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] From this definition, it's apparent one may define the joinability relation as ${\stackrel {*}{\rightarrow }}\circ {\stackrel {*}{\leftarrow }}$ , where $\circ$ is the composition of relations.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Joinability is usually denoted, somewhat confusingly, also with $\downarrow$ , but in this notation the down arrow is a binary relation, i.e. we write $x\mathrel {\downarrow } y$ if *x* and *y* are joinable.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] An ARS is said to possess the *Church–Rosser property* if and only if $x{\stackrel {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ implies $x\mathrel {\downarrow } y$ for all objects *x*, *y*.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Equivalently, the Church–Rosser property means that the reflexive transitive symmetric closure is contained in the joinability relation.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Barkley Rosser proved in 1936 that lambda calculus has this property; hence the name of the property.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In an ARS with the Church–Rosser property the word problem may be reduced to the search for a common successor.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In a Church–Rosser system, an object has *at most one* normal form; that is, the normal form of an object is unique if it exists, but it may well not exist.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Various properties, simpler than Church–Rosser, are equivalent to it.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] The existence of these equivalent properties allows one to prove that a system is Church–Rosser with less work.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Furthermore, the notions of confluence can be defined as properties of a particular object, something that's not possible for Church–Rosser.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Because of these equivalences, a fair bit of variation in definitions is encountered in the literature.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] For instance, in Terese the Church–Rosser property and confluence are defined to be synonymous and identical to the definition of confluence presented here; Church–Rosser as defined here remains unnamed, but is given as an equivalent property; this departure from other texts is deliberate.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Because of the above corollary, one may define a normal form *y* of *x* as an irreducible *y* with the property that $x{\stackrel {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] This definition, found in Book and Otto, is equivalent to the common one given here in a confluent system, but it is more inclusive in a non-confluent ARS.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] Local confluence on the other hand is not equivalent with the other notions of confluence given in this section, but it is strictly weaker than confluence.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] The typical counterexample is $\{b\rightarrow c,c\rightarrow b,b\rightarrow a,c\rightarrow d\}$ , which is locally confluent but not confluent (cf. picture).
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] An abstract rewriting system is said to be **terminating** or *noetherian* if there is no infinite chain $x_{0}\rightarrow x_{1}\rightarrow x_{2}\rightarrow \cdots$ .
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] (This is just saying that the rewriting relation is a Noetherian relation.) In a terminating ARS, every object has at least one normal form, thus it is normalizing.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In example 1 for instance, there is an infinite rewriting chain, namely $a\rightarrow b\rightarrow a\rightarrow b\rightarrow \cdots$ , even though the system is normalizing.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] A confluent and terminating ARS is called **canonical**, or **convergent**.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] In a convergent ARS, every object has a unique normal form.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] But it is sufficient for the system to be confluent and normalizing for a unique normal to exist for every element, as seen in example 1.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] The original 1942 proof of this result by Newman was rather complicated.
[src:term-rewriting/abstract-rewriting-system] It wasn't until 1980 that Huet published a much simpler proof exploiting the fact that when $\rightarrow$ is terminating we can apply well-founded induction.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] A **critical pair** arises in a term rewriting system when two rewrite rules overlap to yield two different terms.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] In more detail, (*t*1, *t*2) is a critical pair if there is a term *t* for which two different applications of a rewrite rule (either the same rule applied differently, or two different rules) yield the terms *t*1 and *t*2.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] The actual definition of a critical pair is slightly more involved as it excludes pairs that can be obtained from critical pairs by substitution and orients the pair based on the overlap.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] When both sides of the critical pair can reduce to the same term, the critical pair is called *convergent*.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] Where one side of the critical pair is identical to the other, the critical pair is called *trivial*.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] Both of these terms can be derived from the term *f*(*g*(*x*,*y*),*z*) by applying a single rewrite rule.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] By applying this rule in two different ways to the term *f*(*f*(*x*,*x*),*x*), we see that (*f*(*x*,*x*), *f*(*x*,*x*)) is a (trivial) critical pair.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] Confluence clearly implies convergent critical pairs: if any critical pair ⟨*a*, *b*⟩ arises, then *a* and *b* have a common reduct and thus the critical pair is convergent.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] If the term rewriting system is not confluent, the critical pair may not converge, so critical pairs are potential sources where confluence will fail.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] The **critical pair lemma** states that a term rewriting system is weakly (a.k.a. locally) confluent if and only if all critical pairs are convergent.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] Thus, to find out if a term rewriting system is weakly confluent, it suffices to test all critical pairs and see if they are convergent.
[src:term-rewriting/critical-pair-logic] This makes it possible to find out algorithmically if a term rewriting system is weakly confluent or not, given that one can algorithmically check if two terms converge.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] In computer science, **graph transformation**, or **graph rewriting**, concerns the technique of creating a new graph out of an original graph algorithmically.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] It has numerous applications, ranging from software engineering (software construction and also software verification) to layout algorithms and picture generation.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Graph transformations can be used as a computation abstraction.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The basic idea is that if the state of a computation can be represented as a graph, further steps in that computation can then be represented as transformation rules on that graph.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Such rules consist of an original graph, which is to be matched to a subgraph in the complete state, and a replacing graph, which will replace the matched subgraph.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Formally, a graph rewriting system usually consists of a set of graph rewrite rules of the form $L\rightarrow R$ , with L being called pattern graph (or left-hand side) and R being called replacement graph (or right-hand side of the rule).
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] A graph rewrite rule is applied to the host graph by searching for an occurrence of the pattern graph (pattern matching, thus solving the subgraph isomorphism problem) and by replacing the found occurrence by an instance of the replacement graph.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Rewrite rules can be further regulated in the case of labeled graphs, such as in string-regulated graph grammars.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The algebraic approach to graph rewriting is based upon category theory.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The algebraic approach is further divided into sub-approaches, the most common of which are the *double-pushout (DPO) approach* and the *single-pushout (SPO) approach*.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Other sub-approaches include the *sesqui-pushout* and the *pullback approach*.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] From the perspective of the DPO approach a graph rewriting rule is a pair of morphisms in the category of graphs and graph homomorphisms between them: $r=(L\leftarrow K\rightarrow R)$ , also written $L\supseteq K\subseteq R$ , where $K\rightarrow L$ is injective.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The graph K is called *invariant* or sometimes the *gluing graph*.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] A *rewriting step* or *application* of a rule r to a *host graph* G is defined by two pushout diagrams both originating in the same morphism $k\colon K\rightarrow D$ , where D is a *context graph* (this is where the name *double*-pushout comes from).
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Another graph morphism $m\colon L\rightarrow G$ models an occurrence of L in G and is called a *match*.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Practical understanding of this is that L is a subgraph that is matched from G (see subgraph isomorphism problem), and after a match is found, L is replaced with R in host graph G where K serves as an interface, containing the nodes and edges which are preserved when applying the rule.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The graph K is needed to attach the pattern being matched to its context: if it is empty, the match can only designate a whole connected component of the graph G .
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] In contrast a graph rewriting rule of the SPO approach is a single morphism in the category of labeled multigraphs and *partial mappings* that preserve the multigraph structure: $r\colon L\rightarrow R$ .
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Thus a rewriting step is defined by a single pushout diagram.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Practical understanding of this is similar to the DPO approach.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The difference is, that there is no interface between the host graph G and the graph G' being the result of the rewriting step.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] From the practical perspective, the key distinction between DPO and SPO is how they deal with the deletion of nodes with adjacent edges, in particular, how they avoid that such deletions may leave behind "dangling edges".
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The DPO approach only deletes a node when the rule specifies the deletion of all adjacent edges as well (this *dangling condition* can be checked for a given match), whereas the SPO approach simply disposes the adjacent edges, without requiring an explicit specification.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] There is also another algebraic-like approach to graph rewriting, based mainly on Boolean algebra and an algebra of matrices, called *matrix graph grammars*.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Yet another approach to graph rewriting, known as *determinate* graph rewriting, came out of logic and database theory.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Another approach to graph rewriting is term graph rewriting, which involves the processing or transformation of term graphs (also known as *abstract semantic graphs*) by a set of syntactic rewrite rules.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Term graphs are a prominent topic in programming language research since term graph rewriting rules are capable of formally expressing a compiler's operational semantics.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Term graphs are also used as abstract machines capable of modelling chemical and biological computations as well as graphical calculi such as concurrency models.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Term graphs can perform automated verification and logical programming since they are well-suited to representing quantified statements in first order logic.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Symbolic programming software is another application for term graphs, which are capable of representing and performing computation with abstract algebraic structures such as groups, fields and rings.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The TERMGRAPH conference focuses entirely on research into term graph rewriting and its applications.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Graph rewriting systems naturally group into classes according to the kind of representation of graphs that are used and how the rewrites are expressed.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] The term graph grammar, otherwise equivalent to graph rewriting system or graph replacement system, is most often used in classifications.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Graphs are an expressive, visual and mathematically precise formalism for modelling of objects (entities) linked by relations; objects are represented by nodes and relations between them by edges.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Nodes and edges are commonly typed and attributed.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] Computations are described in this model by changes in the relations between the entities or by attribute changes of the graph elements.
[src:term-rewriting/graph-rewriting] They are encoded in graph rewrite/graph transformation rules and executed by graph rewrite systems/graph transformation tools.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] In theoretical computer science, in particular in automated reasoning about formal equations, **reduction orderings** are used to prevent endless loops.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] **Rewrite orders**, and, in turn, **rewrite relations**, are generalizations of this concept that have turned out to be useful in theoretical investigations.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] Intuitively, a reduction order *R* relates two terms *s* and *t* if *t* is properly "simpler" than *s* in some sense.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] For example, simplification of terms may be a part of a computer algebra program, and may be using the rule set { *x*+0 → *x* , 0+*x* → *x* , *x**0 → 0, 0**x* → 0, *x**1 → *x* , 1**x* → *x* }.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] In order to prove impossibility of endless loops when simplifying a term using these rules, the reduction order defined by "*sRt* if term *t* is properly shorter than term *s*" can be used; applying any rule from the set will always properly shorten the term.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] In contrast, to establish termination of "distributing-out" using the rule *x**(*y*+*z*) → *x***y*+*x***z*, a more elaborate reduction order will be needed, since this rule may blow up the term size due to duplication of *x*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] The theory of rewrite orders aims at helping to provide an appropriate order in such cases.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] Formally, a binary relation (→) on the set of terms is called a **rewrite relation** if it is closed under contextual embedding and under instantiation; formally: if *l*→*r* implies *u*[*l*σ]*p*→*u*[*r*σ]*p* for all terms *l*, *r*, *u*, each path *p* of *u*, and each substitution σ.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] If (→) is also irreflexive and transitive, then it is called a **rewrite ordering**, or **rewrite preorder**.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] If the latter (→) is moreover well-founded, it is called a **reduction ordering**, or a **reduction preorder**.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] Given a binary relation *R*, its **rewrite closure** is the smallest rewrite relation containing *R*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewrite-order] A transitive and reflexive rewrite relation that contains the subterm ordering is called a **simplification ordering**.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In mathematics, linguistics, computer science, and logic, **rewriting** covers a wide range of methods of replacing subterms of a formula with other terms.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Such methods may be achieved by **rewriting systems** (also known as **rewrite systems**, **rewrite engines**, or **reduction systems**).
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In their most basic form, they consist of a set of objects, plus relations on how to transform those objects.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] One rule to rewrite a term could be applied in many different ways to that term, or more than one rule could be applicable.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Rewriting systems then do not provide an algorithm for changing one term to another, but a set of possible rule applications.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] When combined with an appropriate algorithm, however, rewrite systems can be viewed as computer programs, and several theorem provers and declarative programming languages are based on term rewriting.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In logic, the procedure for obtaining the conjunctive normal form (CNF) of a formula can be implemented as a rewriting system.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For each rule, each variable denotes a subexpression, and the symbol ( $\to$ ) indicates that an expression matching the left hand side of it can be rewritten to one matching the right hand side of it.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In such a system, each rule is a logical equivalence, so performing a rewrite on an expression by these rules does not change the truth value of it.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Other useful rewriting systems in logic may not preserve truth values, see e.g. equisatisfiability.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Term rewriting systems can be employed to compute arithmetic operations on natural numbers.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] To this end, each such number has to be encoded as a term.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The simplest encoding is the one used in the Peano axioms, based on the constant 0 (zero) and the successor function *S*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For example, the numbers 0, 1, 2, and 3 are represented by the terms 0, S(0), S(S(0)), and S(S(S(0))), respectively.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The following term rewriting system can then be used to compute sum and product of given natural numbers.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] where the notation above each arrow indicates the rule used for each rewrite.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] where the last step comprises the previous example computation.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In linguistics, phrase structure rules, also called **rewrite rules**, are used in some systems of generative grammar, as a means of generating the grammatically correct sentences of a language.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Such a rule typically takes the form ${\rm {A\rightarrow X}}$ , where A is a syntactic category label, such as noun phrase or sentence, and X is a sequence of such labels or morphemes, expressing the fact that A can be replaced by X in generating the constituent structure of a sentence.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For example, the rule ${\rm {S\rightarrow NP\ VP}}$ means that a sentence can consist of a noun phrase (NP) followed by a verb phrase (VP); further rules will specify what sub-constituents a noun phrase and a verb phrase can consist of, and so on.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] From the above examples, it is clear that we can think of rewriting systems in an abstract manner.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] We need to specify a set of objects and the rules that can be applied to transform them.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The most general (unidimensional) setting of this notion is called an *abstract reduction system* or *abstract rewriting system* (abbreviated *ARS*).
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An ARS is simply a set *A* of objects, together with a binary relation → on *A* called the *reduction relation*, *rewrite relation* or just *reduction*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The word problem for an ARS is determining, given *x* and *y*, whether $x{\overset {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An object *x* in *A* is called *reducible* if there exists some other *y* in *A* such that $x\rightarrow y$ ; otherwise it is called *irreducible* or a normal form.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An object *y* is called a "normal form of *x*" if $x{\stackrel {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ , and *y* is irreducible.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] If the normal form of *x* is unique, then this is usually denoted with $x{\downarrow }$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] If every object has at least one normal form, the ARS is called *normalizing*. $x\downarrow y$ or *x* and *y* are said to be *joinable* if there exists some *z* with the property that $x{\overset {*}{\rightarrow }}z{\overset {*}{\leftarrow }}y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An ARS is said to possess the Church–Rosser property if $x{\overset {*}{\leftrightarrow }}y$ implies $x\downarrow y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An ARS is confluent if for all *w*, *x*, and *y* in *A*, $x{\overset {*}{\leftarrow }}w{\overset {*}{\rightarrow }}y$ implies $x\downarrow y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An ARS is *locally confluent* if and only if for all *w*, *x*, and *y* in *A*, $x\leftarrow w\rightarrow y$ implies $x{\mathbin {\downarrow }}y$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] An ARS is said to be *terminating* or *noetherian* if there is no infinite chain $x_{0}\rightarrow x_{1}\rightarrow x_{2}\rightarrow \cdots$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A confluent and terminating ARS is called *convergent* or *canonical*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Important theorems for abstract rewriting systems are that an ARS is confluent iff it has the Church–Rosser property, Newman's lemma (a terminating ARS is confluent if and only if it is locally confluent), and that the word problem for an ARS is undecidable in general.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A *string rewriting system* (SRS), also known as *semi-Thue system*, exploits the free monoid structure of the strings (words) over an alphabet to extend a rewriting relation, R , to *all* strings in the alphabet that contain left- and respectively right-hand sides of some rules as substrings.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Formally a semi-Thue system is a tuple $(\Sigma ,R)$ where $\Sigma$ is a (usually finite) alphabet, and R is a binary relation between some (fixed) strings in the alphabet, called the set of *rewrite rules*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The *one-step rewriting relation* ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ induced by R on $\Sigma ^{*}$ is defined as: if $s,t\in \Sigma ^{*}$ are any strings, then $s{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ if there exist $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ such that $s=xuy$ , $t=xvy$ , and $uRv$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Since ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ is a relation on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the pair $(\Sigma ^{*},{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }})$ fits the definition of an abstract rewriting system.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Since the empty string is in $\Sigma ^{*}$ , R is a subset of ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] If the relation R is symmetric, then the system is called a *Thue system*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In a SRS, the reduction relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}$ is compatible with the monoid operation, meaning that $x{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}y$ implies $uxv{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}uyv$ for all strings $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Similarly, the reflexive transitive symmetric closure of ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ , denoted ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ , is a congruence, meaning it is an equivalence relation (by definition) and it is also compatible with string concatenation.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is called the *Thue congruence* generated by R .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In a Thue system, i.e. if R is symmetric, the rewrite relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}}$ coincides with the Thue congruence ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The notion of a semi-Thue system essentially coincides with the presentation of a monoid.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Since ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is a congruence, we can define the factor monoid ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}=\Sigma ^{*}/{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ of the free monoid $\Sigma ^{*}$ by the Thue congruence.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] If a monoid ${\mathcal {M}}$ is isomorphic with ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}$ , then the semi-Thue system $(\Sigma ,R)$ is called a monoid presentation of ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] We immediately get some very useful connections with other areas of algebra.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For example, the alphabet $\{a,b\}$ with the rules $\{ab\rightarrow \varepsilon ,ba\rightarrow \varepsilon \}$ , where $\varepsilon$ is the empty string, is a presentation of the free group on one generator.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] If instead the rules are just $\{ab\rightarrow \varepsilon \}$ , then we obtain a presentation of the bicyclic monoid.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Thus semi-Thue systems constitute a natural framework for solving the word problem for monoids and groups.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In fact, every monoid has a presentation of the form $(\Sigma ,R)$ , i.e. it may always be presented by a semi-Thue system, possibly over an infinite alphabet.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The word problem for a semi-Thue system is undecidable in general; this result is sometimes known as the *Post–Markov theorem*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A **term rewriting system** (**TRS**) is a rewriting system whose objects are *terms*, which are expressions with nested sub-expressions.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For example, the system shown under *§ Logic* above is a term rewriting system.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The terms in this system are composed of binary operators $(\vee )$ and $(\wedge )$ and the unary operator $(\neg )$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Also present in the rules are variables, which represent any possible term (though a single variable always represents the same term throughout a single rule).
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In contrast to string rewriting systems, whose objects are sequences of symbols, the objects of a term rewriting system form a term algebra.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A term can be visualized as a tree of symbols, the set of admitted symbols being fixed by a given signature.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] As a formalism, term rewriting systems have the full power of Turing machines, that is, every computable function can be defined by a term rewriting system.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Some programming languages are based on term rewriting.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] One such example is Pure, a functional programming language for mathematical applications.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A *rewrite rule* is a pair of terms, commonly written as $l\rightarrow r$ , to indicate that the left-hand side *l* can be replaced by the right-hand side *r*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A *term rewriting system* is a set *R* of such rules.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A rule $l\rightarrow r$ can be *applied* to a term *s* if the left term l matches some subterm of *s*, that is, if there is some substitution $\sigma$ such that the subterm of s rooted at some position *p* is the result of applying the substitution $\sigma$ to the term l.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The subterm matching the left hand side of the rule is called a **redex** or **reducible expression**.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] The result term *t* of this rule application is then the result of replacing the subterm at position *p* in *s* by the term r with the substitution $\sigma$ applied, see picture 1.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] In this case, s is said to be *rewritten in one step*, or *rewritten directly*, to t by the system R , formally denoted as $s\rightarrow _{R}t$ , $s{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ , or as $s{\overset {R}{\rightarrow }}t$ by some authors.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] A term rewriting given by a set R of rules can be viewed as an abstract rewriting system as defined above, with terms as its objects and ${\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}$ as its rewrite relation.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For example, $x*(y*z)\rightarrow (x*y)*z$ is a rewrite rule, commonly used to establish a normal form with respect to the associativity of * .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] That rule can be applied at the numerator in the term ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{1*(2*3)}}$ with the matching substitution $\{x\mapsto a,\;y\mapsto a+1,\;z\mapsto a+2\}$ , see picture 2.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Applying that substitution to the rule's right-hand side yields the term $(a*(a+1))*(a+2)$ , and replacing the numerator by that term yields ${\frac {(a*(a+1))*(a+2)}{1*(2*3)}}$ , which is the result term of applying the rewrite rule.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Altogether, applying the rewrite rule has achieved what is called "applying the associativity law for * to ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{1*(2*3)}}$ " in elementary algebra.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Alternately, the rule could have been applied to the denominator of the original term, yielding ${\frac {a*((a+1)*(a+2))}{(1*2)*3}}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Termination issues of rewrite systems in general are handled in *Abstract rewriting system#Termination and convergence*.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] For term rewriting systems in particular, the following additional subtleties are to be considered.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Termination even of a system consisting of one rule with a linear left-hand side is undecidable.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Termination is also undecidable for systems using only unary function symbols; however, it is decidable for finite ground systems.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] All these properties are satisfied by Toyama's examples.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] See Rewrite order and Path ordering (term rewriting) for ordering relations used in termination proofs for term rewriting systems.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Higher-order rewriting systems are a generalization of first-order term rewriting systems to lambda terms, allowing higher order functions and bound variables.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Various results about first-order TRSs can be reformulated for HRSs as well.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Graph rewrite systems are another generalization of term rewrite systems, operating on graphs instead of (ground-) terms / their corresponding tree representation.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Trace theory provides a means for discussing multiprocessing in more formal terms, such as via the trace monoid and the history monoid.
[src:term-rewriting/rewriting] Rewriting can be performed in trace systems as well.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] In theoretical computer science and mathematical logic a **string rewriting system** (**SRS**), historically called a **semi-Thue system**, is a rewriting system over strings from a (usually finite) alphabet.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Thus they constitute a natural framework for solving the word problem for monoids and groups.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] An SRS can be defined directly as an abstract rewriting system.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] It can also be seen as a restricted kind of a term rewriting system, in which all function symbols have an arity of at most 1.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] As a formalism, string rewriting systems are Turing complete.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The semi-Thue name comes from the Norwegian mathematician Axel Thue, who introduced systematic treatment of string rewriting systems in a 1914 paper.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Thue introduced this notion hoping to solve the word problem for finitely presented semigroups.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Only in 1947 was the problem shown to be undecidable— this result was obtained independently by Emil Post and A.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] If the relation R is symmetric, then the system is called a **Thue system**.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The rewriting rules in R can be naturally extended to other strings in $\Sigma ^{*}$ by allowing substrings to be rewritten according to R .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Since ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{}}$ is a relation on $\Sigma ^{*}$ , the pair $(\Sigma ^{*},{\xrightarrow[{R}]{}})$ fits the definition of an abstract rewriting system.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Obviously R is a subset of ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{}}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] A zero-or-more-steps rewriting like this is captured by the reflexive transitive closure of ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{}}$ , denoted by ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}$ (see abstract rewriting system#Basic notions).
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] This is called the **rewriting relation** or **reduction relation** on $\Sigma ^{*}$ induced by R .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] In general, the set $\Sigma ^{*}$ of strings on an alphabet forms a free monoid together with the binary operation of string concatenation (denoted as $\cdot$ and written multiplicatively by dropping the symbol).
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] In a SRS, the reduction relation ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}$ is compatible with the monoid operation, meaning that $x{\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}y$ implies $uxv{\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}uyv$ for all strings $x,y,u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Since ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}$ is by definition a preorder, $\left(\Sigma ^{*},\cdot ,{\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}\right)$ forms a monoidal preorder.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The relation ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is called the **Thue congruence** generated by R.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] In a Thue system, i.e. if R is symmetric, the rewrite relation ${\xrightarrow[{R}]{*}}$ coincides with the Thue congruence ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Since ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ is a congruence, we can define the **factor monoid** ${\mathcal {M}}_{R}=\Sigma ^{*}/{\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ of the free monoid $\Sigma ^{*}$ by the Thue congruence in the usual manner.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] For example, the alphabet {*a*, *b*} with the rules { *ab* → ε, *ba* → ε }, where ε is the empty string, is a presentation of the free group on one generator.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] If instead the rules are just { *ab* → ε }, then we obtain a presentation of the bicyclic monoid.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] In this context, the set $\Sigma$ is called the **set of generators** of ${\mathcal {M}}$ , and R is called the set of **defining relations** ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Post proved the word problem (for semigroups) to be undecidable in general, essentially by reducing the halting problem for Turing machines to an instance of the word problem (see *Post correspondence problem*).
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Concretely, Post devised an encoding as a finite string of the state of a Turing machine plus tape, such that the actions of this machine can be carried out by a string rewrite system acting on this string encoding.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The strings that are valid encodings of Turing machine states start with an h , followed by zero or more symbol letters, followed by exactly one internal state letter $q_{i}$ (which encodes the state of the machine), followed by one or more symbol letters, followed by an ending h .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The symbol letters are straight off the contents of the tape, and the internal state letter marks the position of the head; the symbol after the internal state letter is that in the cell currently under the head of the Turing machine.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] with one instance for each symbol $S_{p}$ in that cell to the left.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Because all rewrites involve one internal state letter $q_{i}$ , the valid encodings only contain one such letter, and each rewrite produces exactly one such letter, the rewrite process exactly follows the run of the Turing machine encoded.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] This proves that string rewrite systems are Turing complete.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The reason for having two halted symbols $q_{r+1}$ and $q_{r+2}$ is that we want all halting Turing machines to terminate at the same *total* state, not just a particular *internal* state.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] This requires clearing the tape after halting, so $q_{r+1}$ eats the symbol on it left until reaching the h , where it transitions into $q_{r+2}$ which instead eats the symbol on its right.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] (In this phase the string rewrite system no longer simulates a Turing machine, since that cannot remove cells from the tape.) After all symbols are gone, we have reached the terminal string $hq_{r+2}h$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] A decision procedure for the word problem would then also yield a procedure for deciding whether the given Turing machine terminates when started in a particular total state t , by testing whether t and $hq_{r+2}h$ belong to the same congruence class with respect to this string rewrite system.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Hence if M does *not* halt when started from t , i.e., if we do *not* have $t\mathrel {\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\rightarrow }}} hq_{r+2}h$ , then we also do *not* have $t\mathrel {\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}} hq_{r+2}h$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Therefore, deciding ${\overset {*}{\underset {R}{\leftrightarrow }}}$ tells us the answer to the halting problem for M .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] However, that there is some Turing machine with undecidable halting problem means that the halting problem for a *universal* Turing machine is undecidable (since that can simulate any Turing machine), and concrete examples of universal Turing machines have been constructed.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] A semi-Thue system is also a term-rewriting system—one that has monadic words (functions) ending in the same variable as the left- and right-hand side terms, e.g. a term rule $f_{2}(f_{1}(x))\rightarrow g(x)$ is equivalent to the string rule $f_{1}f_{2}\rightarrow g$ .
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] A semi-Thue system is also a special type of Post canonical system, but every Post canonical system can also be reduced to an SRS.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Both formalisms are Turing complete, and thus equivalent to Noam Chomsky's unrestricted grammars, which are sometimes called *semi-Thue grammars*.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] A formal grammar only differs from a semi-Thue system by the separation of the alphabet into terminals and non-terminals, and the fixation of a starting symbol amongst non-terminals.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] A minority of authors actually define a semi-Thue system as a triple $(\Sigma ,A,R)$ , where $A\subseteq \Sigma ^{*}$ is called the *set of axioms*.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Under this "generative" definition of semi-Thue system, an unrestricted grammar is just a semi-Thue system with a single axiom in which one partitions the alphabet into terminals and non-terminals, and makes the axiom a nonterminal.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The simple artifice of partitioning the alphabet into terminals and non-terminals is a powerful one; it allows the definition of the Chomsky hierarchy based on what combination of terminals and non-terminals the rules contain.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] This was a crucial development in the theory of formal languages.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] In quantum computing, the notion of a quantum Thue system can be developed.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Since quantum computation is intrinsically reversible, the rewriting rules over the alphabet $\Sigma$ are required to be bidirectional (i.e. the underlying system is a Thue system, not a semi-Thue system).
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Semi-Thue systems were developed as part of a program to add additional constructs to logic, so as to create systems such as propositional logic, that would allow general mathematical theorems to be expressed in a formal language, and then proven and verified in an automatic, mechanical fashion.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] The hope was that the act of theorem proving could then be reduced to a set of defined manipulations on a set of strings.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] It was subsequently realized that semi-Thue systems are isomorphic to unrestricted grammars, which in turn are known to be isomorphic to Turing machines.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] This method of research succeeded and now computers can be used to verify the proofs of mathematic and logical theorems.
[src:term-rewriting/string-rewriting-system] Davis also asserts that the proof was offered independently by A.
